1.Part I

1.1. COVID Analysis

Within the pandemic period, many countries followed different solution ways such as herd immunity, vaccine or quarantine. All these strategies brought out both positive and negative outcomes. However nowadays, people get acquainted with this virus, so governments usually don’t want to alarm the people anymore. This action obviously lead to inaccurate COVID-19 data among people. Since Turkey underreports the COVID test results and statistical data, the pandemic loses its importance naturally. Thus,the precautions that are not taken by communities causes really crucial consequences and the increase in the possibility of recurrence of COVID-19.

1.2. EDA Workflow

My EDA workflow is as follows: - Clean the data: I make some modifications in dataset in order to manipulate it easily. i.e. arranging time or changing the column names. - Make some calculations: I calculate some numbers which might be helpful later on. - Plot some graphs: I create basic plots to understand the data better. - Main Analysis: The main theme in my mind is implemented in this part of my workflow. - Comments and References: After I explain all of my analysis, I add a references part. Then, my explatory data analysis is done. If I had the sample dataset in the question, I would use my workflow again and present the argument that I am inclined to. Since EDA process is a subjective process (in my opinion), I examine the data in my way. To distribute the fund in a fair way, I also search the need for these subjects in the country and determine where there is a deficiency. To sum up, I perform my personal analysis without ignoring some facts and the things what data say.

1.3. starwars Dataset

In this analysis, the column “films” in starwars dataset is generally not used for manipulation due to its vector values. So, I tried to benefit from this column. I used the function, unnest, so that the combined data is splitted and become available. I wonder how many movies the actors/actresses perform and count them. Thus, a new data frame how_many_movies is created.

starwars<-starwars
starwars<-starwars %>% unnest(films) 
how_many_movies<-starwars%>%group_by(name)%>%count()

The plot shows the number of films for each actor/actress and their names.

how_many_movies%>%ggplot(aes(x=name,y=n))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity",position="dodge",fill="orange")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 80, vjust = .5)) +
  ylab("Number of Movies")+
  xlab("Names")

2. Part II: Extended Analysis of the Group Project (Tourist Visits to Turkey)

In this part, I examine the country based percentage of visits to Turkey as an improvement.The percentages of visits for all the countries and continents are calculated with respect to the months and years. In this way, the contribution of foreign countries to Turkey’s tourism sector can be analyzed yearly and monthly.

First of all, I studied on the monthly percentages of touristic visits. By grouping data_pivot based on months and countries, the total numbers of tourists for each country are calculated. Then, I calculated the total number of monthly visits regardless of the countries. By joining these two datasets I get the required data so that the monthly touristic percentage can be calculated.

countries_by_month<-data_pivot%>%group_by(Month,Country)%>%summarize(total_monthly=sum(value))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'Month' (override with `.groups` argument)
total_monthly<-data_pivot%>%group_by(Month)%>%summarize(total_monthly=sum(value))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
data_monthly<-countries_by_month%>%left_join(total_monthly,by="Month")
data_monthly<-data_monthly[!grepl("Total|Africa|Other", data_monthly$Country),]
colnames(data_monthly)[3]  <- "Visits"
colnames(data_monthly)[4]  <- "Total by Month"
data_monthly<-data_monthly%>%mutate(Percentage=100*(Visits/`Total by Month`))

This plot indicates the monthly percentages of touristic visits to Turkey according to each country but continents or regions. (Continents and regions are removed from the data since they cause a confusion in the data analysis.)

data_monthly%>%ggplot(aes(x=Country,y=Percentage))+
  geom_point(aes(color=factor(Month)))+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 80, vjust = .5,size=6))+
  ggtitle("The Monthly Percentage of Visits for all Countries")+
  facet_wrap(~Month)

If the dataset data_monthly is examined closely, it can be observed that the countries which generate tourists with the highest monthly percentages are as follows:

3.2. Explotory Data Analysis

Car Sales data is arranged. Time column is moved to first column.

car_data<-car_data[,c(ncol(car_data),1:(ncol(car_data)-1))]

To have an insight about the data, some sales analysis are conducted. These code and the plot show that the brand with maximum total sales, year by year.

data_total_year<-car_data%>%group_by(brand_name,year)%>%summarise(total=sum(total_total))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'brand_name' (override with `.groups` argument)
data_total_year<-data_total_year%>%group_by(year)%>%filter(total==max(total))

data_total_year%>%ggplot(aes(x=year,y=total,fill=brand_name))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity",position = "dodge")+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=2014:2020)+
  ylab("Total Sales")

After, I want to look the data closely. I conducted an analysis which indicates total monthly sales with respect to brands. To do that, the data is grouped by months and brand_name. Then, in order to see the bars of the brands with lower sales number, I split data_monthly into two group: greater than 500 sales and the lowers.

data_monthly<-car_data%>%group_by(brand_name,month)%>%summarise(mean_total=mean(total_total))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'brand_name' (override with `.groups` argument)
data_monthly_small<-data_monthly%>%filter(mean_total<=500)
data_monthly_big<-data_monthly%>%filter(mean_total>500)

The graph for each dataset are plotted by using faceting.

data_monthly_small%>%ggplot(aes(x=factor(month),y=mean_total,fill=as.factor(brand_name)))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity",position = "dodge")+
  facet_wrap(~as.factor(brand_name))

data_monthly_big%>%ggplot(aes(x=factor(month),y=mean_total,fill=as.factor(brand_name)))+
  geom_bar(stat="identity",position = "dodge")+
  facet_wrap(~as.factor(brand_name))

My main theme about car_data is as follows:

I want to observe the foreign dependency in car sales by looking at the imported and domestic car sales ratio. When the ratio of domestic/imported is higher than “1”, internal trading is appreciated. After calculating the percentages, I find the difference between them. In this way, the change of the dependency in time (monthly) can be observed. When any difference value among the variables (diff1, diff2 and diff3) is negative, it means that external dependency is increasing in car sales. In contrast, if diff values are greater than “0”, then internal trade gains value.

diff1 represents the difference for automobile, diff2 represents the difference for commercial vehicle and diff3 indicates the difference for all type of car sales.

car_data<-add_column(car_data, Percentage1 = car_data$auto_dom/car_data$auto_imp, .after = "auto_imp")
car_data<-add_column(car_data, Percentage2 = car_data$comm_dom/car_data$comm_imp, .after = "comm_imp")
car_data<-add_column(car_data, Percentage3 = car_data$total_dom/car_data$total_imp, .after = "total_imp")

data_ordered<-arrange(car_data,car_data$brand_name)
incremental_data<-data_ordered%>%group_by(brand_name)%>%summarise(diff1=diff(Percentage1),diff2=diff(Percentage2), diff3=diff(Percentage3))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'brand_name' (override with `.groups` argument)
incremental_data<-incremental_data %>% group_by(brand_name) %>% mutate(time = row_number())
incremental_data%>%filter(brand_name=="TOYOTA")
